Definition: [λύω] a primary verb; to "loosen" (literally or figuratively) Compare {{g4486}}.
[λύχνος] from the base of {{g3022}}; a portable lamp or other illuminator (literally or figuratively)
[λυχνία] from {{g3088}}; a lamp-stand (literally or figuratively)
[λυτρωτής] from {{g3084}}; a redeemer (figuratively)
[λύτρωσις] from {{g3084}}; a ransoming (figuratively)
[λυτρόω] from {{g3083}}; to ransom (literally or figuratively)
[λύτρον] from {{g3089}}; something to loosen with, i.e. a redemption price (figuratively, atonement)
[Λύστρα] of uncertain origin; Lystra, a place in Asia Minor
[λυσιτελεῖ] third person singular present indicative active of a derivative of a compound of {{g3080}} and {{g5056}}; impersonally, it answers the purpose, i.e. is advantageous
[λύσις] from {{g3089}}; a loosening, i.e. (specially), divorce
[λείπω] a primary verb; to leave, i.e. (intransitively or passively) to fail or be absent
[λεῖος] apparently a primary word; smooth, i.e. "level"
[λεῖμμα] from {{g3007}}; a remainder

[λέγω] a primary verb; properly, to "lay" forth, i.e. (figuratively) relate (in words (usually of systematic or set discourse; whereas {{g2036}} and {{g5346}} generally refer to an individual expression or speech respectively; while {{g4483}} is properly to break silence merely, and {{g2980}} means an extended or random harangue)); by implication, to mean
[λεγεών] of Latin origin; a "legion", i.e. Roman regiment (figuratively)
[Λεββαῖος] of uncertain origin; Lebbæus, a Christian
[λάχανον] from λαχαίνω (to dig); a vegetable
[λειτουργία] from {{g3008}}; public function (as priest ("liturgy") or almsgiver)
[λειτουργέω] from {{g3011}}; to be a public servant, i.e. (by analogy) to perform religious or charitable functions (worship, obey, relieve)
[Λουκᾶς] contracted from Latin ; Lucas, a Christian
[λοιποῦ] genitive case singular of the same as {{g3062}}; remaining time
[λουτρόν] from {{g3068}}; a bath, i.e. (figuratively), baptism
[Λούκιος] of Latin origin; illuminative; Lucius, a Christian
[λοιμός] of uncertain affinity; a plague (literally, the disease, or figuratively, a pest)
[λοίδορος] from λοιδός (mischief); abusive, i.e. a blackguard
[λοιπόν] neuter singular of the same as {{g3062}}; something remaining (adverbially)
[λοιποί] masculine plural of a derivative of {{g3007}}; remaining ones
[Λύδδα] of Hebrew origin ({{h3850}}); Lydda (i.e. Lod), a place in Palestine
[λούω] a primary verb; to bathe (the whole person; whereas {{g3538}} means to wet a part only, and {{g4150}} to wash, cleanse garments exclusively)
[Μαγώγ] of Hebrew origin ({{h4031}}); Magog, a foreign nation, i.e. (figuratively) an Antichristian party
[Μαδιάν] of Hebrew origin ({{h4080}}); Madian (i.e. Midian), a region of Arabia
[Λωΐς] of uncertain origin; Lois, a Christian woman
[Λώτ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3876}}); Lot, a patriarch
[Μαάθ] probably of Hebrew origin; Maath, an Israelite
[Μαγδαλά] of Chaldee origin (compare {{h4026}}); the tower; Magdala (i.e. Migdala), a place in Palestine
[Μαγδαληνή] feminine of a derivative of {{g3093}}; a female Magdalene, i.e. inhabitant of Magdala
[μαγεία] from {{g3096}}; "magic"
[μαγεύω] from {{g3097}}; to practice magic
[μάγος] of foreign origin ({{h7248}}); a Magian, i.e. Oriental scientist; by implication, a magician
[λειτουργικός] from the same as {{g3008}}; functional publicly ("liturgic"); i.e. beneficient
[λειτουργός] from a derivative of {{g2992}} and {{g2041}}; a public servant, i.e. a functionary in the Temple or Gospel, or (genitive case) a worshipper (of God) or benefactor (of man)
[λέντιον] of Latin origin; a "linen" cloth, i.e. apron
[λεπίς] from λέπω (to peel); a flake
[λέπρα] from the same as {{g3013}}; scaliness, i.e. "leprosy"
[λεπρός] from the same as {{g3014}}; scaly, i.e. leprous (a leper)
[λεπτόν] neuter of a derivative of the same as {{g3013}}; something scaled (light), i.e. a small coin
[Λευΐ] of Hebrew origin ({{h3878}}); Levi, the name of three Israelites Compare {{g3018}}.
[Λευΐς] a form of {{g3017}}; Lewis (i.e. Levi), a Christian
[Λευΐτης] from {{g3017}}; a Levite, i.e. descendant of Levi
[λυπέω] from {{g3077}}; to distress; reflexively or passively, to be sad
[λύπη] apparently a primary word; sadness
[λύκος] perhaps akin to the base of {{g3022}} (from the whitish hair); a wolf
[λυμαίνομαι] middle voice from a probably derivative of {{g3089}} (meaning filth); properly, to soil, i.e. (figuratively) insult (maltreat)
[Λυκαονιστί] adverb from a derivative of {{g3071}}; Lycaonistically, i.e. in the language of the Lycaonians
[Λυκία] probably remotely from {{g3074}}; Lycia, a province of Asia Minor
[Λυδία] properly, feminine of Ludios (of foreign origin) (a Lydian, in Asia Minor); Lydia, a Christian woman
[Λυκαονία] perhaps remotely from {{g3074}}; Lycaonia, a region of Asia Minor
[Λυσανίας] from {{g3080}} and ἀνία (trouble); grief-dispelling; Lysanias, a governor of Abilene
[Λυσίας] of uncertain affinity; Lysias, a Roman
[λίνον] probably a primary word; flax, i.e. (by implication) "linen"
[λιμός] probably from {{g3007}} (through the idea of destitution); a scarcity of food
[λίμνη] probably from {{g3040}} (through the idea of nearness of shore); a pond (large or small)
[λιμήν] apparently a primary word; a harbor Compare {{g2568}}.
[λίψ] probably from λείβω (to pour a "libation"); the south(- west) wind (as bringing rain, i.e. (by extension) the south quarter)
[λίτρα] of Latin origin (libra); a pound in weight
[λιπαρός] from λίπος (grease); fat, i.e. (figuratively) sumptuous
[Λίνος] perhaps from {{g3043}}; Linus, a Christian
[λογίζομαι] middle voice from {{g3056}}; to take an inventory, i.e. estimate (literally or figuratively)
[λογία] from {{g3056}} (in the commercial sense); a contribution
[λοιδορέω] from {{g3060}}; to reproach, i.e. vilify
[λοιδορία] from {{g3060}}; slander or vituperation
[λογομαχέω] from a compound of {{g3056}} and {{g3164}}; to be disputatious (on trifles)
[λογομαχία] from the same as {{g3054}}; disputation about trifles ("logomachy")

[λόγος] from {{g3004}}; something said (including the thought); by implication, a topic (subject of discourse), also reasoning (the mental faculty) or motive; by extension, a computation; specially, (with the article in John) the Divine Expression (i.e. Christ)
[λόγχη] perhaps a primary word; a "lance"
[λογικός] from {{g3056}}; rational ("logical")
[λόγιον] neuter of {{g3052}}; an utterance (of God)
[λόγιος] from {{g3056}}; fluent, i.e. an orator
[λογισμός] from {{g3049}}; computation, i.e. (figuratively) reasoning (conscience, conceit)
[λίαν] of uncertain affinity; much (adverbially)
[λῆμψις] from {{g2983}}; receipt (the act)
[λευκαίνω] from {{g3022}}; to whiten
[Λευϊτικός] from {{g3019}}; Levitic, i.e. relating to the Levites
[λέων] a primary word; a "lion"
[λευκός] from λύκη ("light"); white
[ληνός] apparently a primary word; a trough, i.e. wine-vat
[λήθη] from {{g2990}}; forgetfulness
[λῃστής] from ληΐζομαι (to plunder); a brigand
[λῆρος] apparently a primary word; twaddle, i.e. an incredible story
[λιθόστρωτος] from {{g3037}} and a derivative of {{g4766}}; stone-strewed, i.e. a tessellated mosaic on which the Roman tribunal was placed
[λικμάω] from λικμός, the equivalent of λίκνον (a winnowing fan or basket); to winnow, i.e. (by analogy), to triturate
[Λιβερτῖνος] of Latin origin; a Roman freedman
[Λιβύη] probably from {{g3047}}; Libye, a region of Africa
[λίβανος] of foreign origin ({{h3828}}); the incense-tree, i.e. (by implication) incense itself
[λιβανωτός] from {{g3030}}; frankincense, i.e. (by extension) a censer for burning it
[λιθοβολέω] from a compound of {{g3037}} and {{g906}}; to throw stones, i.e. lapidate
[λίθος] apparently a primary word; a stone (literally or figuratively)
[λιθάζω] from {{g3037}}; to lapidate
[λίθινος] from {{g3037}}; stony, i.e. made of stone
[μαθητεύω] from {{g3101}}; intransitively, to become a pupil; transitively, to disciple, i.e. enrol as scholar
